BINARY TREE TYPES – QUICK SUMMARY

1. Full Binary Tree
- Every node has either 0 or 2 children

2. Perfect Binary Tree
- All nodes have 2 children (except leaves)
- All leaves are at the same level
- Total nodes = 2^h - 1

3. Complete Binary Tree
- All levels are completely filled except possibly the last
- Last level is filled from left to right (no gaps)

4. Incomplete Binary Tree
- Not complete
- Has gaps in the last level (not filled left to right)

5. Imperfect Binary Tree
- Any tree that is not perfect
- Leaves may be at different levels

6. Balanced Binary Tree
- Height difference between left and right subtree ≤ 1

7. Unbalanced Binary Tree
- Height difference > 1
- Can degrade to O(n) performance

8. Degenerate (Skewed) Tree
- Each node has only one child
- Looks like a linked list

9. Binary Search Tree (BST)
- Left subtree < root < right subtree
- Used for searching/sorting

10. Heap (Binary Heap)
- Complete binary tree
- Min Heap: parent ≤ children
- Max Heap: parent ≥ children


BigO:

Lookup, Insert, remove: O(log n) 


